@node Introduction "Stripper v1.2 Documentation"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Stripper simply cuts off the beginning of a file, strips it. The cut off
part can be moved to the end of another file, a "backup" file. You must
specify how many bytes you want the file you're stripping to become.
Stripper won't cut the file in the middle of a line though. It finds the
nearest start of a line towards the beginning of the file and cuts there
instead. Hence, the stripped file will be bigger than, or equal to, the
size you specified.

@endnode

@node WhyUseful "Stripper v1.2 Documentation"

Why It Could Be Useful
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you're running an AmiExpress BBS, some files tend to grow quite large,
for example the CallersLog, UDLog and DoorLog. To keep them constantly at
a reasonable size, use Stripper! There are many doors that search through
these files, so they shouldn't be too large, or else it could take a while
for the doors to handle them. Note that Stripper doesn't check if it cuts
the files in the middle of a "user" (a call), it just makes sure it
doesn't cut in the middle of a line. You could for example call it in your
logoff script, or run it once a day (with some Cron program) or once a
week. That's up to you.

The terminal program TERM maintains (as default) a file called
term-action.log where all your actions are recorded, such as connects,
downloads, uploads and disconnects. That file can eventually grow very
large, and that's where Stripper comes into the picture...

It's up to you to think of all the other possibilities.
@endnode

@node Requirements "Stripper v1.2 Documentation"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Stripper requires an Amiga with AmigaDOS 2.0 or higher to run.

@endnode

@node Usage "Stripper v1.2 Documentation"

How to Use It
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The command line syntax is as follows:

strip <stripfile> <size> [<backupfile>]

<stripfile> is the name of the file that will get its beginning cut off.
<size> is the desired size in bytes for the stripfile, which will be cut
at the nearest beginning of a line, towards the beginning of the file. If
you specify a backup file, the cut off part will be appended to it.

Some examples:

strip bbs:node0/CallersLog 100000

This call strips the file bbs:node0/CallersLog so that is becomes 100000
bytes big, or perhaps a few bytes bigger so that it won't be cut in the
middle of a line.

strip bbs:node0/CallersLog 100000 bbs:node0/CLogBackup

This accomplishes the same as the previous call, but the cut-off part will
be appended to the file bbs:node0/CLogBackup.
@endnode

